<TITLE> Bangladesh signs 50,000 tonnes rice deal with India </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Feb 21 (bdnews24.com)The government Wednesday signed a deal with India, clearing the latest hurdle for importing 50,000 tonnes of rice in the first shipment from the neighbouring country, an adviser said. Food adviser AMM Shawkat Ali told bdnews24.com by phone that the first shipment would arrive in Bangladesh in 15 days from now. The deal was signed in Kolkata. "We want the shipment to be sent from India by rail and road," he said. The two countries will sign a separate deal on the remaining 4.5 lakh tonnes of rice through the government channel. India pledged to export a total of 5 lakh tonnes of rice to Bangladesh through the government channel but put restrictions on the exports of non-basmati rice through private channels, in what it said was to feed its own people. The prices of rice to be imported through the government channel have been set at $399 per tonne on average. The government will use four routesroad, rail, river and seato bring in all the shipments. The shipment by sea will cost $414, and shipments carried by train and road will cost $388 per tonne. The shipment by river will be $400. bdnews24.co
